HEADWORD: Presagement
<hw>Pre*sage"ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or art of presaging; a foreboding.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which is presaged, or foretold.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Ominous <xex>presagement</xex> before his end.
⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Sir H. Wotton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Presager</ent>⟦br⟧
